Subject: Is true multi-platform CM just an ILLUSION ???
Date: 16 Dec 1994 10:43:09 GMT
Organization: Oslonett public access
Message-ID: <3crqvu$962@hasle.oslonett.no>

OK, my company has UNIX, Windows, NT, and OS/2, and
we make client-server software that runs on multiple
platforms. A typical system involves a server part
running on either UNIX or NT, and clients
running on Windows or OS/2.

I need to establish a configuration management system
that works for all these different platforms. So I need
a software tool according to the following requirements:

- The tool should be able to version control text and binaries.
- The tool should know what a project is, and what a
  project contains.
- The tool should know what a project stage is, like design,
  development, testing, release, and production.
- The tool should support hierarchies of components, i.e. it
  should know what a module is.
- The tool should know what a platform and architecture is,
  and support the make/build process.
- The tool should support the test phase, including module
  tests, where a development version of one module is
  tested together with more established versions of other
  modules.
- The tool should support patch versions.
- The tool should support problem tracking.
- The tool should have both a command-line based interface
  and a GUI for each platform.
- It should be possible to put the tool's server (repository)
  on any platform.

We have RCS, PVCS, SourceSafe, CCC/Harvest and others, but it
SEEMS LIKE THERE IS NO TOOL THAT CAN DO IT ALL!!!!

And without it, then multi-platform configuration management
is truly an ILLUSION.

I still hope I am wrong, but I doubt it...

